\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 2.             Aristolochia }           L.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By P.W. Ball (Ed.1) revised by E. Nardi & J.R. Akeroyd(Ed.2)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial herbs or woody climbers. Flowers axillary. Perianth zygomorphic, deciduous, the base swollen (utricle), the upper part narrower, more or less cylindrical (tube), with single, entire lobe (limb), rarely absent or 3-lobed. Stamens usually 6, in 1 whorl, connate with stylar column. Fruit a septicidal capsule.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b A. macrophylla} Lam.,{\i  Encycl.Méth. Bot.}{\b  1:} 252 (1783) ({\i A. durior} Hill,{\i  A. sipho} L'Hér.), from North America, a woody climber with cordate leaves up to 30 cm and perianth brownish with a 3-lobed limb, is cultivated for ornament, and is reported to be naturalized in Germany.
